WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.720
Welcome to the follow-up game.

2
00:00:02.160 --> 00:00:05.280
I'm going to say it three times because it's
that important.

3
00:00:05.700 --> 00:00:07.700
Follow-up, follow-up, follow-up.

4
00:00:08.020 --> 00:00:11.360
Why? Because follow-up is where deals
actually happen.

5
00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:15.400
That's not a pep talk, it's just how the
math works in this business.

6
00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:18.920
Most deals do not close on the first call.

7
00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:20.580
They close on the second call.

8
00:00:20.940 --> 00:00:23.360
The third call. Sometimes the seventh call.

9
00:00:23.700 --> 00:00:28.480
The sellers who eventually sign contracts
are the ones who had somebody stay in touch

10
00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:29.900
with them consistently.

11
00:00:30.620 --> 00:00:32.620
Professionally and with real care.

12
00:00:33.220 --> 00:00:35.440
Not the person who called once and then
vanished.

13
00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:40.080
Here's what's actually going on when a lead
hits your CRM.

14
00:00:40.500 --> 00:00:42.640
That seller is dealing with a lot.

15
00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:46.540
They've probably gotten calls from multiple
investors already.

16
00:00:46.700 --> 00:00:50.880
They're navigating whatever situation pushed
them towards selling in the first place.

17
00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:56.680
Whether that's financial pressure, a divorce,
an inherited property, or just being done

18
00:00:56.680 --> 00:00:57.740
with being a landlord.

19
00:00:57.940 --> 00:00:59.880
They might not be ready to make a decision.

20
00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:03.920
But not ready today does not mean not
interested.

21
00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:06.640
It means the timing hasn't lined up yet.

22
00:01:06.640 --> 00:01:09.420
Or their situation hasn't gotten urgent
enough.

23
00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:12.860
Or they haven't built enough trust with
anyone calling them.

24
00:01:13.380 --> 00:01:15.720
Or they just need more time to sit with it.

25
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.620
Your job is to be the person who's there
when they're ready.

26
00:01:19.880 --> 00:01:22.440
Not the person who tried once and moved on.

27
00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:26.400
The industry data on this is pretty wild.

28
00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:29.860
Most follow-up in real estate investing
stops after a few days.

29
00:01:29.860 --> 00:01:31.320
After one or two attempts.

30
00:01:31.920 --> 00:01:34.920
But most deals close after five or more
touches.

31
00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:39.060
So if you're the person making that fifth or
sixth contact while everybody else quit

32
00:01:39.060 --> 00:01:41.800
after two, you're the one who gets the deal.

33
00:01:42.120 --> 00:01:45.260
It's not complicated. It just takes
discipline.

34
00:01:46.280 --> 00:01:51.020
Here's the follow-up cadence we use at BMH
for active leads.

35
00:01:51.540 --> 00:01:55.320
On the first day, you have your initial call
or conversation.

36
00:01:55.980 --> 00:01:58.740
You log your notes and schedule the
follow-up.

37
00:01:58.940 --> 00:02:01.680
On day two, you send a follow-up text.

38
00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:05.640
Something short and personal, not a mass
blast.

39
00:02:05.640 --> 00:02:11.340
Day four, you make a follow-up call and
reference the previous conversation.

40
00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:15.920
Day seven, you call again and send a text if
they don't answer.

41
00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:21.320
Day 14, follow-up call with a new angle or
new piece of information.

42
00:02:21.820 --> 00:02:25.240
Day 21, send a text or email to check in.

43
00:02:25.420 --> 00:02:29.660
Day 30, another call with a simple, any
changes on your end?

44
00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:34.300
After day 30, you shift to a monthly
cadence.

45
00:02:34.840 --> 00:02:40.280
One touch per month, alternating between
calls and texts for up to six months.

46
00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:46.580
If after six months of consistent follow-up,
there's been absolutely zero engagement.

47
00:02:47.140 --> 00:02:50.160
No answered calls. No returned texts.

48
00:02:50.540 --> 00:02:55.820
No responses at all. You can move the lead
to long-term nurture or market dead.

49
00:02:56.600 --> 00:03:01.160
The first call is all about discovery and
qualification.

50
00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:06.860
Calls to and beyond are different because
you're not starting from scratch anymore.

51
00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:11.680
You're building on a relationship that
already exists, even if it's a thin one.

52
00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:15.240
For the second call, it sounds something
like this.

53
00:03:15.860 --> 00:03:18.300
Hey, this is Andrea with the BMH Group.

54
00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:22.220
We talked a few days ago about your property
at 123 Main Street.

55
00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:26.760
I wanted to follow-up and see if you've had
a chance to think about what we discussed.

56
00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:31.540
How are things going? The key there is
referencing the previous conversation.

57
00:03:32.220 --> 00:03:35.040
It shows them you remember who they are.

58
00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:40.380
For the third call and beyond, you need to
bring something new each time.

59
00:03:40.980 --> 00:03:42.320
Don't just call to check in.

60
00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:44.840
That's lazy and the seller can feel it.

61
00:03:45.040 --> 00:03:50.020
Instead, share something relevant like, I
was looking at some recent sales in your area

62
00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:51.760
and wanted to share what I found.

63
00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:55.100
Or ask about something they mentioned last
time.

64
00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:58.740
You mentioned your brother was coming into
town to help with the property.

65
00:03:59.180 --> 00:04:01.220
Did you get a chance to talk with him about
it?

66
00:04:01.860 --> 00:04:05.420
Every follow-up should have a reason beyond,
are you ready yet?

67
00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:09.240
Now, sellers go silent sometimes.

68
00:04:09.860 --> 00:04:14.780
It happens. They were engaged on the first
call, said they'd think about it, and then

69
00:04:14.780 --> 00:04:18.320
nothing. No answered calls, no returned
texts.

70
00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:20.860
Don't panic and don't write them off.

71
00:04:21.420 --> 00:04:26.160
This is where ghost texts come in, which are
strategically written messages designed to

72
00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:28.460
get a response from someone who's gone
quiet.

73
00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:31.700
You can try a casual check-in.

74
00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:34.040
Hey, it's Andrea from the BMH Group.

75
00:04:34.660 --> 00:04:35.760
Haven't heard from you in a bit.

76
00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:37.840
Just wanted to make sure you're doing okay.

77
00:04:38.240 --> 00:04:39.560
Any updates on the property?

78
00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:41.860
Or try an assumptive approach.

79
00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:47.140
Hi, I wanted to let you know we're still
interested in your property at 123 Main Street.

80
00:04:47.340 --> 00:04:49.600
If the timing isn't right, no worries at
all.

81
00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:52.020
Just let me know and I'll update my notes.

82
00:04:52.020 --> 00:04:54.240
There's also the value add angle.

83
00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:56.940
Hey, I noticed some activity in your
neighborhood.

84
00:04:57.300 --> 00:04:59.200
A few properties have sold recently.

85
00:04:59.580 --> 00:05:02.540
Wanted to see if that changes anything on
your end.

86
00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:07.820
And then there's the simple yes, no, which
is surprisingly effective.

87
00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:12.240
Hi, still thinking about selling the
property at 123 Main Street?

88
00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:14.820
Just a quick yes or no and I'll know how to
help.

89
00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:18.120
You do need to know when to stop, though.

90
00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:20.820
Follow-up should be persistent, not
annoying.

91
00:05:21.260 --> 00:05:27.560
There is a line. If they explicitly say,
stop calling me or remove me from your list,

92
00:05:27.880 --> 00:05:29.640
you respect that immediately.

93
00:05:29.640 --> 00:05:33.360
Mark it in the CRM and stop all contact.

94
00:05:33.780 --> 00:05:39.180
Full stop. If you've had six months of zero
engagement across every channel, move them

95
00:05:39.180 --> 00:05:41.620
to long-term nurture or mark the lead dead.

96
00:05:41.940 --> 00:05:44.060
Everything else, keep following up.

97
00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:46.840
Not right now means follow-up later.

98
00:05:47.540 --> 00:05:51.180
I need to think about it means follow-up in
a few days.

99
00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:56.940
Call me next month means you put it in the
CRM and you call them next month.

100
00:05:56.940 --> 00:05:59.980
People tell you exactly when to call them
back.

101
00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:01.620
Take them at their word.

102
00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:05.960
The biggest challenge with follow-up isn't
knowing what to do.

103
00:06:06.100 --> 00:06:11.780
It's actually doing it consistently every
single day, even when you don't feel like it.

104
00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:17.040
That means at the start of each day, your
follow-up list in Sandra is your number one

105
00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:21.200
priority. Follow-ups happen before new
leads, always.

106
00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:26.900
If you have 30 follow-ups scheduled for
today, you make all 30 attempts.

107
00:06:27.140 --> 00:06:31.260
If you can't reach someone, you leave a
voicemail and send a text.

108
00:06:31.520 --> 00:06:36.940
And you never, ever skip a follow-up because
you've decided in your head that they

109
00:06:36.940 --> 00:06:38.040
probably aren't interested.

110
00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:41.920
You don't know that. The seller hasn't told
you that.

111
00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:43.440
So you make the call.

112
00:06:44.280 --> 00:06:49.520
The person who does their follow-ups every
day without exception will outperform the

113
00:06:49.520 --> 00:06:54.880
person who makes twice as many new calls but
ignores their follow-up list every single

114
00:06:54.880 --> 00:06:55.300
time.

115
00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:56.620
That's not an opinion.

116
00:06:56.660 --> 00:06:59.820
It's what we've seen play out over and over
again.

117
00:07:00.340 --> 00:07:03.860
Your roleplay for this module is a probate
lead in St.

118
00:07:03.960 --> 00:07:04.210
Louis.

119
00:07:04.640 --> 00:07:10.520
It's an inherited house, emotionally complex,
and the seller needs your empathy just as

120
00:07:10.520 --> 00:07:11.680
much as your persistence.

121
00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:14.780
Once you've run the roleplay, meet me in the
next lesson.

122
00:07:14.900 --> 00:07:17.520
We're pulling every script you've learned
into one flow.
